EPISODE_NARRATIVE: June was feast or famine for rainfall across South Central Texas. Most of the region had less than 50 percent of normal. However, the southwestern corner of the area received in excess of 150 percent of normal and parts of Maverick and Dimmit Counties had as much as four times normal. This rain allowed Kinney (now in extreme drought category, Stage D3), Dimmit (severe category, Stage D2), Maverick (D2), and Zavala (D2) Counties to improve their drought conditions. At the same time, the lack of rain led to drought conditions worsening to stage D3 in Bastrop and Lee Counties, and to stage D2 in Blanco, Burnet, Caldwell, Comal, Fayette, Gonzales, Guadalupe, Hays, Kendall, and Travis Counties. Val Verde (D4), Edwards (D3), Bandera (D2), De Witt (D2), Frio (D2), Gillespie (D2), Kerr (D2), Llano (D2), Medina (D2), Real (D2), Uvalde (D2), and Williamson (D2) Counties all remained unchanged from May. Fire danger at the end of the month was moderate. Of the counties in D2 or worse drought Caldwell, Dimmit, Edwards, Fayette, Frio, Kinney, Lee, Llano, Maverick, Medina, and Val Verde had outdoor burn bans in effect at the end of the month. The seven day stream flow averages were much below normal (less than 10 percent) across the Colorado River basin. The Upper and Middle Guadalupe, Nueces, Rio Grande, and Frio River basins were reporting below normal (10 to 24 percent) flow. Area lakes and reservoirs continued well below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was around 59 feet below normal. Lake Travis was 54 feet below normal and Medina Lake 83 feet below normal which left it at 5 percent of capacity. The Edwards Aquifer was nearly 17 feet below normal, and 3.2 feet below the level at the end of June 2012. Uvalde was in stage 5 water restrictions, Austin was in stage 2, and Kerrville, San Marcos, and Seguin were in stage 1. The Barton Springs Edwards Aquifer Conservation District was in stage 3 alarm drought status.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very unstable airmass developed across North Central Louisiana during the later afternoon and evening hours of June 28th.  A strong frontal boundary was moving through Central and Southern Arkansas during the late afternoon, producing isolated strong to severe thunderstorms as the storms tracked south.  Cloud bases were elevated in nature and an isolated severe thunderstorm developed across Ouachita Parish near the Monroe, Louisiana area.  This thunderstorm quickly became severe producing damaging thunderstorm wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees and powerlines were downed in and around Monroe, Louisiana.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very unstable airmass developed across North Central Louisiana during the later afternoon and evening hours of June 28th.  A strong frontal boundary was moving through Central and Southern Arkansas during the late afternoon, producing isolated strong to severe thunderstorms as the storms tracked south.  Cloud bases were elevated in nature and an isolated severe thunderstorm developed across Ouachita Parish near the Monroe, Louisiana area.  This thunderstorm quickly became severe producing damaging thunderstorm wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Isolated severe thunderstorm collapsed near the Monroe Regional Airport producing a 77 mph wind gust.  Several aircraft hangers were reported to be damaged and an airplane was also damaged near the tarmac.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A long period swell from the southern hemisphere generated surf of 6 to 12 feet along the south-facing shores of all the main Hawaiian Islands.  In a few instances, water from the high surf flowed over adjacent roads and deposited sand and other debris.||Lifeguards were busy throughout the episode, rescuing more than 100 surfers and swimmers, and issuing several hundreds of warnings.  One surfer died from injuries suffered at Ala Moana Bowls on Oahu on June 6th, while another male on the same day on Oahu sustained serious injuries while surfing at Sandy Beach.  There were no reports of serious property damage.
A late afternoon thunderstorm produced large hail in extreme northeast Laramie County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported in Albin.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed along various boundaries within a warm and moist air mass over the region. Storms first developed across the Finger Lakes midday along the Lake Ontario lake breeze and then in the mid afternoon along the Lake Erie lake breeze boundary as it pushed inland across the Southern Tier. The strongest storms produced one to two inch hailstones.  Specific hail reports were received from Stanley, Geneva, Newark, Walworth, Marion, and Brockport. In several of those locations, automobiles were damage by the hail stones.  Later in the afternoon thunderstorms rolled across the North Country with downed trees and power poles reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A postal carrier reported trees downed by thunderstorm winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Surface high pressure built into the Great Basin, bringing strong and gusty northeast winds through and below passes and canyons during the morning of the 2nd. Winds temporarily decreased that night, before increasing again, somewhat, the morning of the 3rd.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High winds began at the Fremont Canyon RAWS between 0451 and 0551 PST on the 2nd and ended between 0951 and 1051 PST the same day. During this time, winds were sustained 30 to 45 mph with gusts mostly above 60 mph, including the peak gust of 70 mph measured between 0651 and 0751 PST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The residual cold airmass over the Texas Panhandle from a cold frontal passage earlier in the week had begun to modify. This kept overnight low temperatures from cooling as quickly as previous nights. Freezing temperatures were not obtained until the early morning hours on the 5th. These subfreezing temperatures threatened sensitive vegetation during the start of the growing season. Overnight lows ranged from 30 degrees at Hereford (Deaf Smith County) to 31 degrees at Perryton (Ochiltree County). Temperatures quickly warmed above freezing during the late morning of the 5rd.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An overnight low of 30 degrees was reported in Hereford.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous low pressure system swept across the Great Plains during the early morning hours of the 21st. A shortwave trough rotated around the base of this system and helped initiate showers and thunderstorms over the southern Texas Panhandle. However, the forcing was not sufficient for this convection to overcome the strong nocturnal inversion and tap into the marginal elevated instability. The strong deep layer shear easily toppled developing thunderstorms which led to isolated downbursts as thunderstorms collapsed. The shortwave quickly moved to the east, shifting the favorable environment for development out of the Texas Panhandle by the late morning hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorm developed over southern Randall County during the mid-morning hours of the 21st. As the thunderstorm moved to the northeast it encountered a strongly sheared environment which toppled the storm structure. The core of the thunderstorm collapsed 1 mile east of the city of Canyon (Randall County) causing a dangerous cross wind on Interstate 27. This cross wind caused two semi-tractor trailers to be overturned. No injuries were reported in association with this damage, wind speed estimated from similar report in the area, and property damage values estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: May 29th brought a widespread severe weather outbreak to the eastern Texas Panhandle. Morning upper air analysis on the 29th showed a mid-level trough centered from Idaho to New Mexico with a low level closed low over Colorado and the western Oklahoma Panhandle. The lift provided by both of these large scale forcing mechanisms would easily overcome the capping inversion in place across the eastern Texas Panhandle by the early afternoon. At the surface, a dryline was positioned along the Eastern Plains of New Mexico during the morning hours before advancing eastward into the Texas Panhandle. By noon, this dryline had advanced to the central Texas Panhandle before stalling and provided a focusing point for convective initiation. Thunderstorms developed in an area of moderate elevated instability across the eastern Texas Panhandle which promoted rapid vertical growth. In the same area, vertical wind shear was ideal for the development of supercells. Along the dryline, discrete supercell thunderstorms developed shortly after the noon hour. These supercells produced 60+ mph gusts and hail up to the size of hen eggs.  As the afternoon progresses discrete supercells progressed to the east and merged into a squall line. Several more reports of 60+ mph gusts and large hail were received by the National Weather Service Office in Amarillo (Potter County) as this squall line progressed out of the Texas Panhandle and into western Oklahoma shortly after 5 pm CST.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A rapidly intensifying supercell moved to the northeast across southern Grey County. A storm chaser traveling north along US Highway 70 intercepted the storm south of the Farm to Market road 2447 and US Highway 70 intersection. The storm chaser reported that the supercell produced hen egg size hail on US Highway 70. The supercell continued a northeasterly track and crossed Farm to Market road 2477 before merging with a developing squall line.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: May brought some much needed rain to South Central Texas. Much of the area received above normal rainfall and 14 counties moved to better than severe (Stage D2) drought. In addition, Bandera, Kerr, Medina, Real, Uvalde, and Williamson Counties improved a category to stage D2. All the other counties stayed the same with Kinney, Maverick, and Val Verde in exceptional (Stage D4) drought category, Dimmit, Edwards, and Zavala in extreme (Stage D3), and Bastrop, De Witt, Frio, Gillespie, Lee, and Llano in severe (Stage D2) category. Fire danger at the end of the month was low to moderate. Of the counties in D2 or worse drought seven had outdoor burn bans in effect at the end of the month. These were Dimmit, Edwards, Frio, Kinney, Maverick, Medina, and Val Verde. The seven day stream flow averages were much below normal (less than 10 percent) across the Colorado River basin. The Guadalupe, Nueces, Rio Grande, and Frio River basins were reporting below normal (10 to 24 percent) flow. Area lakes and reservoirs continued below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was around 61 feet below normal at 1056.3 feet which is a new record low for the lake. Lake Travis was 52 feet below normal and Medina Lake near 82 feet below normal which left it at 5.5 percent of capacity. The Edwards Aquifer saw some improvement from the rain in May, but was still 8 feet below normal, and 4.2 feet below the level at the end of May 2012. Uvalde was in stage 5 water restrictions and Kerrville was in stage 1.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: May 29th brought a widespread severe weather outbreak to the eastern Texas Panhandle. Morning upper air analysis on the 29th showed a mid-level trough centered from Idaho to New Mexico with a low level closed low over Colorado and the western Oklahoma Panhandle. The lift provided by both of these large scale forcing mechanisms would easily overcome the capping inversion in place across the eastern Texas Panhandle by the early afternoon. At the surface, a dryline was positioned along the Eastern Plains of New Mexico during the morning hours before advancing eastward into the Texas Panhandle. By noon, this dryline had advanced to the central Texas Panhandle before stalling and provided a focusing point for convective initiation. Thunderstorms developed in an area of moderate elevated instability across the eastern Texas Panhandle which promoted rapid vertical growth. In the same area, vertical wind shear was ideal for the development of supercells. Along the dryline, discrete supercell thunderstorms developed shortly after the noon hour. These supercells produced 60+ mph gusts and hail up to the size of hen eggs.  As the afternoon progresses discrete supercells progressed to the east and merged into a squall line. Several more reports of 60+ mph gusts and large hail were received by the National Weather Service Office in Amarillo (Potter County) as this squall line progressed out of the Texas Panhandle and into western Oklahoma shortly after 5 pm CST.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorm moved over the city of Wellington (Collingsworth County) shortly before 5 PM CST on the 29th. A storm chaser on 15th street near the Marian Airpark reported hen egg size hail as the storm passed over their location. No reports of damage accompanied this hail report.

CZ_NAME: SAN BERNARDINO AND RIVERSIDE COUNTY VALLEYS - THE INLAND EMPIRE
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The Summit fire started near N. San Gorgonio Avenue and Summit Drive in Banning (Riverside County) around 1138 PST on the 1st. The brush fire burned rapidly toward the northwest, driven by Santa Ana winds of 30-40 mph, destroying one residence and one out building. The fire threatened 450 homes in and around Cherry Valley, CA. Mandatory evacuations were in place for approximately 750 people there. Two firefighters received unknown injuries. The fire burned a total of 3166 acres before being fully contained around 1700 PST on the 4th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Snow became heavy in part of northwest Iowa during the afternoon of March 10th, and continued into the nighttime hours. Accumulations as high as 14 inches were reported. Northerly winds were gusting to 30 mph at the start of the snowfall, but decreased slowly during the event and only modest drifting was reported. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A significant late season winter storm emerging out of the mid-Mississippi Valley dumped heavy snow over much of western Upper Michigan...especially higher terrain locations along Lake Superior...from the 18th into the 20th.  North winds gusting over 50 mph in the wake of the storm system produced blizzard conditions over the Keweenaw Peninsula on the 19th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The observer at Herman measured nearly 11 inches of storm total snowfall.  North winds gusting to 30 mph at times caused extensive blowing and drifting of snow on the 19th.  The storm forced the early dismissal of schools on the 19th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure moved off the mid Atlantic coast Tuesday night, January 15th, and passed just south of Cape Cod Wednesday afternoon the 16th. Snow associated with this low overspread the Berkshires during the early morning hours Wednesday. Some warmer air worked into the area by early in the afternoon resulting in some sleet, freezing rain and freezing drizzle. The bulk of the precipitation occurred in the morning in the form of snow and impacted the commute resulting in some accidents. Total snowfall reports across Berkshire County ranged from 4 to 6 inches.

A double shot of winter weather impacted north Texas during the day on the 5th and continuing into the 6th. Initially, wintry precipitation came in all forms, with freezing rain, sleet and snow. The second round of winter weather came as primarily snow, though some sleet and freezing rain continued into the morning hours of the 6th. Substantial snow, sleet and ice accumulations were reported over portions of western north Texas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sleet and light freezing rain began during the afternoon of the 5th, continuing into the morning of the 6th. By the time the event ended, an inch and a half of sleet had accumulated in Archer City.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On Friday, December 20th, a shallow but strong cold front surged through southern Oklahoma, bringing a prolonged sub-freezing airmass to all of Oklahoma. From the evening of the 20th through the afternoon of the 21st, a persistent light to moderate freezing rain event occurred, with substantial ice accumulations over a large part of central and southern Oklahoma. Across portions of northern and western Oklahoma, snow accumulations occurred as the cold airmass deepened and an upper trough lifted northeast through central Oklahoma late on the 21st into the 22nd. The ice storm resulted in thousands of power outages across the Oklahoma City metro and surrounding areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Freezing rain prevailed through the event with widespread 1/3 to 1/2 inch ice accumulations on trees, power lines and other elevated surfaces. Downed trees and power lines along with sporadic power outages were also reported in Norman and Moore.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: This snowfall event was a two-part system across Vermont. The first part was largely confined to the northern half of Vermont and occurred during the morning and afternoon hours of February 8th. This event was caused by a relatively strong, but slowly dissipating storm from the Great Lakes into northern New York. Snowfall totals from this event were 4 to 10 inches across the northern half of Vermont with very little across southern Vermont.||The second event was a large, powerful Nor'easter that moved south of Long Island and Cape Cod during the night of February 8th. Snow from this system reached southern Vermont during the evening and continued until mid-morning of February 9th.|Snowfall from this event ranged from 4 to 16 inches with the greatest across the higher terrain of southeast Vermont.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four to eight inches of snow fell across Caledonia county...the higher amounts were largely confined to the higher elevations in western portions of the county away from the shadowing effects of New Hampshire's White mountains.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The fourth lake effect event of the season was a combination of light synoptic snows followed lake effect snows.  Off Lake Erie, snow fell through the morning and afternoon hours of the 18th before migrating northward through the evening hours and dissipating. The lake effect band of snow off Lake Ontario intensified through the late morning and afternoon hours of the 18th while impacting the Tug Hill region. This band too also shifted northward overnight and weakened. Snowfall rates peaked at two inches per hour. Within the higher snowfall rates, thunder snow occurred. Gusty winds and the timing of early morning did bring accidents on area roads slowing the morning commute. Specific amounts reported included:  12 inches at West Falls and Highmarket; 11 inches as Boston and Lacona; 10 inches at Dunkirk and 8 inches as Constableville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The arctic cold front that brought ice, sleet and snow accumulations on December 5th and December 6th stalled along the Gulf Coast on December 7th, 2013. Low pressure developed along the front and spread precipitation northward into North Mississippi during the evening of December 7th into the early morning hours of December 8th. Since arctic air was already in place, precipitation fell in the from of freezing rain and sleet. Anywhere from a tenth of an inch up to a quarter of an inch fell across Northwest Mississippi, from a corridor from Coahoma County to Tippah County. Bridges and overpasses became iced and several accidents occurred as a result.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulations were around a tenth of an inch.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A 170 kt upper level jet dove south out of British Columbia into Washington and Oregon by early Saturday November 16th which provided strong lift and precipitation across north-central Idaho into western Montana. An arctic cold front brought gusty winds and heavy snow at times across Glacier National park and along US-2 from West Glacier to Marias Pass on the 16th.  As the orientation of the upper level jet became more northwesterly by the 17th and moved off to the north and east, showers were felt across much of the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Bearmouth MTDOT web cam on Interstate 90 at milepost 145.8 indicated snow-covered road conditions for at least 3 hours during the morning hours on Nov. 16.  The MacDonald Pass road sensor located at milepost 27.9 on US-12 reported periods of snow between Nov. 16-17 with strong gusty winds to 35 mph. Web cams at MacDonald Pass indicated periods of blowing snow with limited visibility.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A person from the public reported that 6 of heavy wet snow fell from the evening of Nov. 15 through 10:45 am PST Nov. 16. They reported that the heavy snow created difficult driving conditions. The Pierce RS SNOTEL at 3,080 ft., located 9.2 miles west of Pierce, measured 3 snow and 1.40 of precipitation from Nov. 15-17. The Shanghi Summit at 4,570 ft., located 3.5 mi. west-northwest of Cardiff reported 16 of snow with 2.40 of precipitation.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On the 14th, the trough slowly began shifting eastward, allowing dry and warmer offshore flow to develop and providing gusty, northerly high winds through the passes and canyons, filtering down into the Inland Empire, causing some damage in the form of downed power lines and road signs. There were several stations reporting sustained winds of 40 mph or greater and gusts over 60 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On the 14th, the trough slowly began shifting eastward, allowing dry and warmer offshore flow to develop and providing gusty, northerly high winds through the passes and canyons, filtering down into the Inland Empire, causing some damage in the form of downed power lines and road signs. There were several stations reporting sustained winds of 40 mph or greater and gusts over 60 mph.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: CHP reported phone lines blown down in the vicinity of Highway 91 and West 14th Street. A large highway traffic sign and posts were also blown down along Highway 91 eastbound, just west of Arlington Avenue. Both of these reports were between 0400 and 0500 PST on the 14th. Later in the morning, around 0750 PST, another freeway sign was blown down near the Interstate 215 northbound off ramp at Baseline Street. Around 0930 PST that morning, a big rig trailer overturned on Interstate 15 southbound, near the Interstate 10 east connector.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: This snowfall event generally began on the 27th under a moist southwest flow which followed on the heels of a storm which vacated the area earlier on the same day.  However, snowfall actually began for some lower elevation areas of northeast Utah late on the 26th.  The moist southwest flow aloft preceded a potent Pacific trough which moved over eastern Utah on January 28th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totals of 9 to 14 inches were measured above the 8000 foot level.  Additionally, wind gusts of 40 to 60 mph produced areas of blowing and drifting snow, with localized blizzard conditions.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Early on the morning of Saturday, December 21, 2013 an area of light to moderate rain moved northward into eastern Kansas and western Missouri. At the time of the rain surface temperatures were in the middle to upper 20s. The result was several hours of freezing rain across the aforementioned eastern Kansas and western and central Missouri areas, including the Kansas City metro area. Widespread reports of around .25 of ice accumulation were received by the NWS, with the highest report of .45 coming from Clinton, Missouri. After sunset the freezing rain gradually transitioned into sleet, then snow. By 9 pm Saturday night most of the area was receiving light to moderate snow. Areas north of Interstate 70 received about 6 to 8 inches of snow, with some locations reporting higher amounts. The highest official snow total the NWS received was 9.0 from spotters near St. Joseph and Grant City. The snow moved out of the area late Saturday night, leaving behind very slick roads and some minor damage caused by the ice.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Light freezing rain began in north central Missouri during the afternoon hours on December 21. The ASOS station at Kirksville, Missouri (KIRK) recorded .25 of precipitation, while recording freezing rain. Aside from the nearly quarter inch of ice accumulation in and around Kirksville, spotters from across the area reported 4 to 6 inches of snow through the evening and overnight hours on December 21 into the morning of December 22.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The drought that began in June and expanded to become an Exceptional (D4) Drought in 2012 continues into January 2013. While the weather in January was characterized as progressive the storm track provided little relief or recharge to the depleted soil moisture. Short term impacts are expected to hit agriculture and grasslands, while the long-term impacts to hydrological and ecological interests are expected to linger. In January some rainfall did occur although departures remain over four inches that keep fire dangers and potential impacts at the forefront and in the news.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The drought that began in June 2012 continued into January 2013. The exceptional (D4) drought lingered as below normal precipitation fell during the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a cold front stalled out to the east of central Indiana on December 5th and 6th, waves of low pressure rode along the front. These waves generated snow, sleet, and freezing rain across much of central Indiana. By the time the snow ended December 6, up to around 1 foot of snow fell in parts of the area. The most snow fell across southern sections of central Indiana, along with some ice accumulation.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A snowfall observation of 6.8 inches was taken near Greensburg.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stalled frontal boundary across northern portions of the forecast area was the focus for afternoon convection on the afternoon of June 23rd. A weak shortwave swinging in from the west helped to increase wind fields aloft and strong heating south of the front produced CAPES in the 1000 to 1500 j/kg range. Hail and damaging winds were the main threats with these storms, the stronger of which held together long enough to drift into southern portions of the region later in the day.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A severe thunderstorm produced 1 inch hail near Milton.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A swell from a powerful low far northwest of the islands generated surf of 15 to 30 feet along the north- and west-facing shores of Niihau and Kauai, and the north-facing shores of Oahu, Molokai, and Maui; 10 to 20 feet along the west-facing shores of Oahu, Molokai, and Maui; 10 to 15 feet along the west-facing shores of the Big Island of Hawaii; and 8 to 12 feet along the west-facing shores of Lanai and Kahoolawe.||Two men were swept away by the large waves on the north shore of Kauai in the later afternoon of the 18th.  Lifeguards on Oahu, alone, accounted for more than 2000 safety actions with this high surf episode.  Many beaches were closed for a time because of the rough conditions, and several roadways near the shoreline on the individual isles became covered with debris from waves breaking beyond the beach areas.  The costs of any property damage were not available.

Lifeguards on Oahu, alone, accounted for more than 2000 safety actions with this high surf episode.  Many beaches were closed for a time because of the rough conditions, and several roadways near the shoreline on the individual isles became covered with debris from waves breaking beyond the beach areas.  The costs of any property damage were not available.
A band of heavy rain caused small stream and drainage ditch flooding, and ponding on roadways, over portions of Kauai.  There were no reports of significant injuries or property damage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The remnants of Tropical Storm Andrea tracked across southeastern Massachusetts bringing heavy rain (3-5 inches) to much of southern New England.  This resulted in significant urban flooding, particularly across eastern Massachusetts and Rhode Island, as well as river and small stream flooding.  It also contributed to record high rainfall across the area for the month of June.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three to five inches of rain fell across the Providence metro area.  Several basements were flooded along Lockbridge Street in Pawtucket.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moved from the Great Lakes across southern New England bringing showers and thunderstorms to the region.  Most of these storms produced heavy rain, but at least one produced damaging winds in Connecticut.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms produced strong winds that downed several trees and snapped tree branches.

However, a few reports of damage were received in northwestern Ohio.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A surface boundary arched from a low northwest of Jamestown down to near Wahpeton, North Dakota. A tornado formed near the boundary west-southwest of Colfax.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: After the heavy rain that fell on May 31st, numerous roads remained closed around the Park River area.

Thunderstorms formed over the Devils Lake region along a cold frontal boundary and low pressure system. Storms also initiated along the warm front which extended down into southeast North Dakota. Afternoon temperatures topped out in the low to mid 80s with dew points around 70. By mid evening of the 25th the storm tracked into the northwest quarter of Minnesota. Many reports of large hail, strong winds, and heavy rain were received.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A few trees and several large branches were blown down in various shelterbelts in northern Deerhorn Township.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tornado touched down about a mile west of the airport and tracked to the Interstate 94 exit north of town by 2230 CST. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper trough and an associated cold front moved into the Lower Mississippi Valley during the evening of May 21st, 2013. Several rounds of showers and thunderstorms developed ahead of the system affecting the Mid-South. Some storms became severe producing large hail, damaging winds, and flash flooding. The first round of storms moved through during the morning hours while a second round affected the region during the afternoon into the evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain produced flash flooding over portions of Northwest Fayette County. The intersection of Hwy 196 and Orr Road was flooded as a result.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: June was feast or famine for rainfall across South Central Texas. Most of the region had less than 50 percent of normal. However, the southwestern corner of the area received in excess of 150 percent of normal and parts of Maverick and Dimmit Counties had as much as four times normal. This rain allowed Kinney (now in extreme drought category, Stage D3), Dimmit (severe category, Stage D2), Maverick (D2), and Zavala (D2) Counties to improve their drought conditions. At the same time, the lack of rain led to drought conditions worsening to stage D3 in Bastrop and Lee Counties, and to stage D2 in Blanco, Burnet, Caldwell, Comal, Fayette, Gonzales, Guadalupe, Hays, Kendall, and Travis Counties. Val Verde (D4), Edwards (D3), Bandera (D2), De Witt (D2), Frio (D2), Gillespie (D2), Kerr (D2), Llano (D2), Medina (D2), Real (D2), Uvalde (D2), and Williamson (D2) Counties all remained unchanged from May. Fire danger at the end of the month was moderate. Of the counties in D2 or worse drought Caldwell, Dimmit, Edwards, Fayette, Frio, Kinney, Lee, Llano, Maverick, Medina, and Val Verde had outdoor burn bans in effect at the end of the month. The seven day stream flow averages were much below normal (less than 10 percent) across the Colorado River basin. The Upper and Middle Guadalupe, Nueces, Rio Grande, and Frio River basins were reporting below normal (10 to 24 percent) flow. Area lakes and reservoirs continued well below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was around 59 feet below normal. Lake Travis was 54 feet below normal and Medina Lake 83 feet below normal which left it at 5 percent of capacity. The Edwards Aquifer was nearly 17 feet below normal, and 3.2 feet below the level at the end of June 2012. Uvalde was in stage 5 water restrictions, Austin was in stage 2, and Kerrville, San Marcos, and Seguin were in stage 1. The Barton Springs Edwards Aquifer Conservation District was in stage 3 alarm drought status.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An approaching cold front brought showers and thunderstorms to central Illinois during the evening of May 31st. Many of the storms became severe, producing widespread wind damage across the area. Two tornadoes briefly touched down as well. The first tornado occurred in Decatur in Macon County, while the second one touched down just southeast of Westville in Vermilion County. In addition, excessive rainfall rates of 2 to 3 inches per hour associated with some of the storms produced localized flash flooding that lingered into the morning hours of June 1st.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down onto Route 1 just east of Robinson.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front was approaching from the west. Ahead of it temperatures reached their convective temps and wind speeds increased. Thunderstorms formed along a lee trough.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Kings Valley road at Kingstead Road were flooded.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front moved through the Oklahoma Panhandle during the early morning hours of the 1st. The strong post frontal surface pressure gradient caused surface winds to increase into the 35 to 39 mph range for several hours. An isolated high wind gust was reported by the Oklahoma Mesonet site in Goodwell (Texas County) at 5:55 AM CST as stronger upper level winds were able to mix to the surface.  No other high wind gusts were reported after 5:55 am CST since the surface pressure gradient weakened in response to the cold front progressing well into central Texas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Oklahoma Mesonet site in Goodwell reported a 58 mph wind gust at 5:55 AM CST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A collapsing thunderstorm over Potter and Randall County sent an outflow boundary in all directions. To the west of the storm, the outflow boundary was measured to be 58 mph by the Texas Department of Transportation AWOS in Hereford (Deaf Smith County).  No damage was reported in association of this outflow boundary.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hereford AWOS recorded a 58 mph non-thunderstorm wind gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A frontal boundary moved northward and stalled over the Mid-Atlantic/I-95 corridor overnight. An upper level low approached the region and a upper level jet added to enhanced lift in the region. Heavy rain caused a lot of flash flooding with amounts up to seven inches in less than 6 hours recorded near Washington Dulles Airport.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: These roads were closed: River Road, Golfsboro, Macarthur Blvd, Goldleaf and Cabin John Parkway.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong winds aloft moved over northern and central New Mexico within the base of a large scale upper level trough over the western United States.  These winds mixed to the surface in localized areas along and immediately east of the northern mountains where high wind gusts were reported during the predawn hours through the early afternoon.  Elsewhere...widespread windy conditions were reported throughout the day.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Raton ASOS reported sustained winds between 40 and 46 mph throughout the period.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread breezy to windy conditions impacted the region as strong winds aloft continued to combine with a surface trough over eastern NM.  An isolated locale over the south central high terrain reported a peak wind gust to 59 mph for an hour or two during the late afternoon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A peak wind gust to 59 mph was reported 5 miles northwest of Nogal.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: May brought some much needed rain to South Central Texas. Much of the area received above normal rainfall and 14 counties moved to better than severe (Stage D2) drought. In addition, Bandera, Kerr, Medina, Real, Uvalde, and Williamson Counties improved a category to stage D2. All the other counties stayed the same with Kinney, Maverick, and Val Verde in exceptional (Stage D4) drought category, Dimmit, Edwards, and Zavala in extreme (Stage D3), and Bastrop, De Witt, Frio, Gillespie, Lee, and Llano in severe (Stage D2) category. Fire danger at the end of the month was low to moderate. Of the counties in D2 or worse drought seven had outdoor burn bans in effect at the end of the month. These were Dimmit, Edwards, Frio, Kinney, Maverick, Medina, and Val Verde. The seven day stream flow averages were much below normal (less than 10 percent) across the Colorado River basin. The Guadalupe, Nueces, Rio Grande, and Frio River basins were reporting below normal (10 to 24 percent) flow. Area lakes and reservoirs continued below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was around 61 feet below normal at 1056.3 feet which is a new record low for the lake. Lake Travis was 52 feet below normal and Medina Lake near 82 feet below normal which left it at 5.5 percent of capacity. The Edwards Aquifer saw some improvement from the rain in May, but was still 8 feet below normal, and 4.2 feet below the level at the end of May 2012. Uvalde was in stage 5 water restrictions and Kerrville was in stage 1.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous low pressure system swept across the Great Plains during the early morning hours of the 21st. A shortwave trough rotated around the base of this system and helped initiate showers and thunderstorms over the southern Texas Panhandle. However, the forcing was not sufficient for this convection to overcome the strong nocturnal inversion and tap into the marginal elevated instability. The strong deep layer shear easily toppled developing thunderstorms which led to isolated downbursts as thunderstorms collapsed. The shortwave quickly moved to the east, shifting the favorable environment for development out of the Texas Panhandle by the late morning hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorm developed over southern Randall County during the mid-morning hours of the 21st. As the thunderstorm moved to the northeast it encountered a strongly sheared environment which toppled the storm structure. The core of the thunderstorm collapsed 1 mile east of the city of Canyon (Randall County) causing a 61 mph downburst. This downburst was measured by a trained storm spotter near the West Texas A&M University Event Center.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Individual severe thunderstorms that developed over South Central Wisconsin, producing hail up to 1 inch in diameter, merged into several squall lines that produced damaging wind gusts as they moved east through Southeast Wisconsin during the afternoon and evening hours of May 30th. Overall forcing for ascent over the region was provided by  differential vorticity advection ahead of a progressive 500 mb negatively-tilted trough, with the storms developing on the nose of a moderate to strong low-level jet ahead of the wave. Moderate instability, reflected in mixed-layer CAPE values of 1000 to 1200 J/kg, and favorable wind shear contributed to conditions that produced broken bands of thunderstorms with damaging wind gusts and downbursts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Madison TV 27 reported numerous trees and power lines blown down by thunderstorm wind gusts estimated at 65 mph (56 knots) in Middleton. Some cars were damaged by the downed trees, as well as a tree piercing the roof of a condominium. A shed was also destroyed by the damaging thunderstorm wind gusts.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An outflow boundary situated over interstate 80 became the focus for thunderstorm development as several upper level disturbances rounded a flattening ridge over the plains. These storms eventually congealed into several lines, one near the western Pennsylvania/Ohio border and another further back into Ohio southern lower Michigan, that moved southeastward through the evening of the 25th and early on the 26th. In addition to widespread reports of wind damage and hail, training thunderstorms dumped two to four inches of rain and caused areas of flooding across east central Ohio and adjacent areas in western Pennsylvania.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ohio department of highways reported trees down along Route 751.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A trough over the eastern United States combined with deep tropical moisture over the region with a slow moving front sagging southward over Georgia combined with the sea breezes to produce a very active convective day. Thunderstorm activity drifted inland from the SW and Gulf Coast region...with activity further blossoming toward the Atlantic coast and over SE Ga during the afternoon and evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An observer measured 1.8 inches of rainfall within 45 minutes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level low pressure system was moving slowly through Eastern Oklahoma into Western Arkansas during the afternoon hours of May 16th. A lone supercell thunderstorm across North Central Texas developed during the late morning hours of May 16th. This storm developed in a strongly sheared environment which allowed the storm to sustain itself. The storm moved south and east towards a strong instability axis which was oriented across Northeast Texas into Northwest Louisiana. With strong heating, strong instability developed and the supercell thunderstorm intensified as it moved south and east. The storm produced several tornado tracks, some of which occurred in Harrison County Texas and other into Southwest Caddo Parish and Northern Desoto Parish. The storm was a prolific hail and wind producer as well with wind gusts near 100 mph south of Shreveport, Louisiana with large fields of hail which turned numerous acres of land completely white.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees were downed along with power poles.  Some structural damage was also reported.

An upper ridge was over northern Mexico, and abundant moisture was over the area from southeast low level winds.  A surface boundary was present across the Permian Basin with upper level disturbances passing nearby which provided lift.   This lift and moisture combined with good instability to produce hail, strong winds, and flash flooding across New Mexico and West Texas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A cluster of thunderstorms moved across Howard County and produced an estimated 65 mph wind gust in Big Spring.  There was no damage reported with this wind.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The combination of a surface cold front and weak upper level shortwave initiated showers and thunderstorms across the Texas Panhandle during the evening hours of the 8th. At 3 PM CST, the surface cold front had begun to slow as it moved into the western Oklahoma Panhandle. The lift provided by the front had proved sufficient in initiating scattered thunderstorms along the front from northern Kansas to the southwestern Texas Panhandle. By 6PM CST, the cold front was stretched from the eastern Oklahoma Panhandle to the northwest corner of the Texas Panhandle. As the evening hours advanced, a combination of discrete and linear thunderstorms developed across the eastern Oklahoma and northern Texas Panhandle. These thunderstorms stayed along the front while intensifying then advanced to the south-southeast ahead of the front once becoming outflow driven. Thunderstorms continued to move to the south-southeast until exiting the southern Texas Panhandle shortly before midnight on the 9th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A cluster of thunderstorms developed along a stalling cold front during the evening hours of the 8th. This cluster of thunderstorms moved to the south across the northern Texas Panhandle. A trained storm spotter 1 mile west of Booker (Ochiltree County) reported quarter size hail (1 inch). The storm that produced this hail continued moving to the south across the county after producing this hail.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large, intense squall line developed during the afternoon in central Kansas and pushed south through the evening hours. Widespread severe wind gusts, some significant, along with some severe hail occurred in north central Oklahoma. The convection weakened as it moved into central Oklahoma, but the gust front associated with the storms continued to produce severe wind over parts of the Oklahoma City metro area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: At NW 104th and Council. Tree damage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of thunderstorms developed over eastern Tennessee ahead of a cold front. The line pushed east across the mountains and then across the foothills and piedmont during the afternoon and early evening hours. The line formed in an airmass characterized by high instability and moderate wind shear, and several of the storms produced areas of straight-line wind damage and one rare tornado in the North Carolina Mountains. The storms also produced large hail over the foothills and piedmont.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Multiple trees were blown down on across the county, with some trees on homes or power lines.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: April brought some much needed rain to South Central Texas. Most of the eastern half of the area received 150% or more of normal rainfall and only Kinney, Maverick, and Zavala Counties got less than 25% of normal. This rain had a mixed impact on the drought. Edwards (Stage D3), Bastrop (D2), Caldwell (D2), Fayette (D2), and Gonzales (D2) Counties each improved a category. At the same time, Bandera, Comal, Medina, and Uvalde Counties all worsened to Stage D3 and Frio County moved into the D2 stage. Kinney, Maverick, and Val Verde Counties remained in Stage D4. Dimmit, Guadalupe, Hays, Kerr, Real, Williamson, and Zavala Counties remained in Stage D3. Bexar, Blanco, Burnet, De Witt, Gillespie, Karnes, Kendall, Lavaca, Lee, Llano, Travis, and Wilson Counties remained in Stage D2. Fire danger at the end of the month was moderate to high. Of the counties in D2 or worse drought 11 had outdoor burn bans in effect at the end of the month. These were Bexar, Comal, Dimmit, Edwards, Frio, Karnes, Kinney, Maverick, Medina, Val Verde, and Wilson. The Texas Crop and Weather Report issued by Texas A and M Agricultural indicated livestock producers were supplying supplemental feed and de-stocking as necessary. The seven day stream flow averages were much below normal (less than 10 percent) across the Colorado, Guadalupe, Nueces, and Frio River basins. The Rio Grande basin was reporting below normal (10 to 24 percent) flow. Area lakes and reservoirs continued below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was around 60 feet below normal at 1056.9 feet which is a new record low for the lake. Lake Travis was 52 feet below normal and Medina Lake near 82 feet below normal which left it at 5.5 percent of capacity. The Edwards Aquifer saw some improvement from the rain in April, but was still 18.4 feet below normal, and 13.5 feet below the level at the end of April 2012. Uvalde moved into stage 5 water restrictions and the Barton Springs Edwards Aquifer Conservation District into stage 3. San Marcos, Austin, and the San Antonio Water System, were in stage 2, and Kerrville was in stage 1 restrictions.

Dimmit, Guadalupe, Hays, Kerr, Real, Williamson, and Zavala Counties remained in Stage D3. Bexar, Blanco, Burnet, De Witt, Gillespie, Karnes, Kendall, Lavaca, Lee, Llano, Travis, and Wilson Counties remained in Stage D2. Fire danger at the end of the month was moderate to high. Of the counties in D2 or worse drought 11 had outdoor burn bans in effect at the end of the month. These were Bexar, Comal, Dimmit, Edwards, Frio, Karnes, Kinney, Maverick, Medina, Val Verde, and Wilson. The Texas Crop and Weather Report issued by Texas A and M Agricultural indicated livestock producers were supplying supplemental feed and de-stocking as necessary. The seven day stream flow averages were much below normal (less than 10 percent) across the Colorado, Guadalupe, Nueces, and Frio River basins. The Rio Grande basin was reporting below normal (10 to 24 percent) flow. Area lakes and reservoirs continued below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was around 60 feet below normal at 1056.9 feet which is a new record low for the lake. Lake Travis was 52 feet below normal and Medina Lake near 82 feet below normal which left it at 5.5 percent of capacity. The Edwards Aquifer saw some improvement from the rain in April, but was still 18.4 feet below normal, and 13.5 feet below the level at the end of April 2012. Uvalde moved into stage 5 water restrictions and the Barton Springs Edwards Aquifer Conservation District into stage 3. San Marcos, Austin, and the San Antonio Water System, were in stage 2, and Kerrville was in stage 1 restrictions.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front moved through South Central Texas and produced severe thunderstorms. Convection initially began south of the front along a convergence zone, in the warm sector, that moved up from the southeast. Later in the evening, the cold front became more active.

A cold front moved through South Central Texas and produced severe thunderstorms. Convection initially began south of the front along a convergence zone, in the warm sector, that moved up from the southeast. Later in the evening, the cold front became more active.

Early on the morning of Saturday, December 21, 2013 an area of light to moderate rain moved northward into eastern Kansas and western Missouri. At the time of the rain surface temperatures were in the middle to upper 20s. The result was several hours of freezing rain across the aforementioned eastern Kansas and western and central Missouri areas, including the Kansas City metro area. Widespread reports of around .25 of ice accumulation were received by the NWS, with the highest report of .45 coming from Clinton, Missouri. After sunset the freezing rain gradually transitioned into sleet, then snow. By 9 pm Saturday night most of the area was receiving light to moderate snow. Areas north of Interstate 70 received about 6 to 8 inches of snow, with some locations reporting higher amounts. The highest official snow total the NWS received was 9.0 from spotters near St. Joseph and Grant City. The snow moved out of the area late Saturday night, leaving behind very slick roads and some minor damage caused by the ice.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Light to moderate snow picked up during the afternoon hours on December 21. Preceding the snow freezing rain produced some minor icing in and around the area. Once the snow began it quickly accumulated between 5 and 7 inches across the area. The highest amount received came from Princeton, Missouri where 6 to 7 inches of snow fell. While there were several vehicle spin-outs across the area, and despite the ice accumulation the widespread effects were rather minimal.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: This snowfall event was a two-part system across Vermont. The first part was largely confined to the northern half of Vermont and occurred during the morning and afternoon hours of February 8th. This event was caused by a relatively strong, but slowly dissipating storm from the Great Lakes into northern New York. Snowfall totals from this event were 4 to 10 inches across the northern half of Vermont with very little across southern Vermont.||The second event was a large, powerful Nor'easter that moved south of Long Island and Cape Cod during the night of February 8th. Snow from this system reached southern Vermont during the evening and continued until mid-morning of February 9th.|Snowfall from this event ranged from 4 to 16 inches with the greatest across the higher terrain of southeast Vermont.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four to eight inches of snow fell across eastern Chittenden county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The drought that began in June and expanded to become an Exceptional (D4) Drought in 2012 continues into January 2013. While the weather in January was characterized as progressive the storm track provided little relief or recharge to the depleted soil moisture. Short term impacts are expected to hit agriculture and grasslands, while the long-term impacts to hydrological and ecological interests are expected to linger. In January some rainfall did occur although departures remain over four inches that keep fire dangers and potential impacts at the forefront and in the news.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The drought that began in June 2012 continued into January 2013. The exceptional (D4) drought lingered as below normal precipitation fell during the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A surface front stalled across the region acted as a pathway for periods of heavy precipitation. South of the front, rain fell however to the north the precipitation fell as freezing rain. Ice coated trees, power lines and all exposed surfaces. Across the Niagara Frontier, ice accumulations of a half- to one-inch were reported. Across the north country, where the freezing rain persisted the longest, the ice accumulations ranged from one to two inches. The weight of the heavy ice brought down trees and power lines. In some cases, trees fell on homes, buildings and automobiles. Tens of thousands were left without power. New York State issued an Emergency Declaration for Jefferson and Lewis countiesthe hardest hit of the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The arctic cold front that brought ice, sleet and snow accumulations on December 5th and December 6th stalled along the Gulf Coast on December 7th, 2013. Low pressure developed along the front and spread precipitation northward into North Mississippi during the evening of December 7th into the early morning hours of December 8th. Since arctic air was already in place, precipitation fell in the from of freezing rain and sleet. Anywhere from a tenth of an inch up to a quarter of an inch fell across Northwest Mississippi, from a corridor from Coahoma County to Tippah County. Bridges and overpasses became iced and several accidents occurred as a result.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulations were around a tenth of an inch.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure over the southeastern states on the morning of the 29th moved rapidly north-northeastward to Nova Scotia by the morning of the 30th.  The low brought abundant moisture northward and produced 6 to 14 inches of snow across the interior and foothill sections of western Maine.  Along the coast, warmer temperatures caused the precipitation to change to rain.

A 170 kt upper level jet dove south out of British Columbia into Washington and Oregon by early Saturday November 16th which provided strong lift and precipitation across north-central Idaho into western Montana.  As the orientation of the upper level jet became more northwesterly by the 17th and moved off to the north and east, showers were felt across much of the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Dixie COOP observer at 5,740 ft. reported 15.3 of snow with 0.98 of precipitation between Nov. 15-18. A person from the public near Lowell reported that wet snow fell on back-country roads making travel miserable for hunters. The Mountain Meadows SNOTEL at 6,360 ft., located 13.2 miles southeast of Elk City reported 6 of snow with 0.50 of precipitation. The Savage Pass SNOTEL at 6,170 ft. located 5 miles southeast of Powell measured 16 of snow with 1.20 of precipitation. The web cam at Elk City showed snow on state highway 14 during the morning hours on Nov. 16.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Early on the morning of Saturday, December 21, 2013 an area of light to moderate rain moved northward into eastern Kansas and western Missouri. At the time of the rain surface temperatures were in the middle to upper 20s. The result was several hours of freezing rain across the aforementioned eastern Kansas and western and central Missouri areas, including the Kansas City metro area. Widespread reports of around .25 of ice accumulation were received by the NWS, with the highest report of .45 coming from Clinton, Missouri. After sunset the freezing rain gradually transitioned into sleet, then snow. By 9 pm Saturday night most of the area was receiving light to moderate snow. Areas north of Interstate 70 received about 6 to 8 inches of snow, with some locations reporting higher amounts. The highest official snow total the NWS received was 9.0 from spotters near St. Joseph and Grant City. The snow moved out of the area late Saturday night, leaving behind very slick roads and some minor damage caused by the ice.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Light freezing rain began in north central Missouri during the afternoon hours on December 21. The ASOS station at Kirksville, Missouri (KIRK) recorded .25 of precipitation, while recording freezing rain. Aside from the nearly quarter inch of ice accumulation in and around Kirksville, spotters from across the area reported 4 to 6 inches of snow through the evening and overnight hours on December 21 into the morning of December 22.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: In the wake of the ground blizzard on the 19th that affected portions of northeast North Dakota and the extreme northwest corner of Minnesota, frigid air moved into the region. Morning lows across the area on the 21st ranged from 15 below to 25 below zero, while daytime highs mainly stayed below zero. In combination with winds of 10 to 20 mph, wind chill readings dropped to 40 below to 50 below zero at times.

This snowfall event generally began on the 27th under a moist southwest flow which followed on the heels of a storm which vacated the area earlier on the same day. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Numerous thunderstorms developed across Kansas during the mid to late afternoon in an environment of moderate shear and high instability, with very rich low-level moisture. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a cold front stalled out to the east of central Indiana on December 5th and 6th, waves of low pressure rode along the front. These waves generated snow, sleet, and freezing rain across much of central Indiana. By the time the snow ended December 6, up to around 1 foot of snow fell in parts of the area. The most snow fell across southern sections of central Indiana, along with some ice accumulation.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall observations of 7.5 and 9 inches were taken near Bedford and Mitchell, respectively.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The storm track shifted a bit further north in June, keeping the excessive rains confined to about the northeast one-third of the state. The months largest event|came from the 21st to the 23rd with Dorchester recording 8.99 inches of rain. Major|flooding resulted along northeast Iowa rivers such as the Upper Iowa and the Turkey. A second major rain event on the 24th brought 6.80 inches of rain to Lowden and resulted in major flooding along the Wapsipinicon River. Rain totals for the month varied from 2.11 inches at Holly Springs (Woodbury County) and 2.22 inches near Albia to a whopping 14.06 inch total at Dorchester (but still shy of their June record total of 15.13 inches set in 2008). The persistent spring and early summer precipitation has allowed all of Iowa to be rated as drought-free by the U. S. Drought Monitor for the first time since early August 2011. According to Iowa Agricultural Statistics crop planting progress has been the slowest since 1993 with 4% of the soybean acreage, mostly in north central and northeast Iowa, still unplanted at months end. The statewide average year-to-date precipitation total was a record for the first one-half of the year at 25.07 inches or 7.87 inches more than normal. The old record for January through June was 24.46 inches set in 2008 while 2012s total for the entire year was 26.49 inches.  Flooding in the Des Moines CWA was limited to the northeast, or Cedar River system.  Flood waters rose 2 to 5 feet above flood stage in those areas.

As a result, several severe thunderstorms developed behind the front in the very unstable atmosphere. The storms produced damaging winds and large hail. One brief tornado also occurred as two storms merged together.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three horses were struck by lightning and killed.

A swell from a powerful low far northwest of the islands generated surf of 15 to 30 feet along the north- and west-facing shores of Niihau and Kauai, and the north-facing shores of Oahu, Molokai, and Maui; 10 to 20 feet along the west-facing shores of Oahu, Molokai, and Maui; 10 to 15 feet along the west-facing shores of the Big Island of Hawaii; and 8 to 12 feet along the west-facing shores of Lanai and Kahoolawe.||Two men were swept away by the large waves on the north shore of Kauai in the later afternoon of the 18th.  Lifeguards on Oahu, alone, accounted for more than 2000 safety actions with this high surf episode.  Many beaches were closed for a time because of the rough conditions, and several roadways near the shoreline on the individual isles became covered with debris from waves breaking beyond the beach areas.  The costs of any property damage were not available.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper trough and an associated cold front moved into the Lower Mississippi Valley during the evening of May 21st, 2013. Several rounds of showers and thunderstorms developed ahead of the system affecting the Mid-South. Some storms became severe producing large hail, damaging winds, and flash flooding. The first round of storms moved through during the morning hours while a second round affected the region during the afternoon into the evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain produced flash flooding in Batesville. Six businesses reported anywhere from six inches to a foot of standing water in them.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stationary front remained across Northern Mississippi during the early morning hours of May 18th, 2013. The front was a source of continuous development of convection. As a result, heavy rain fell in portions of North Mississippi which produced flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain produced flash flooding in Pontotoc. Several streets were covered with water as a result.

June was feast or famine for rainfall across South Central Texas. Most of the region had less than 50 percent of normal. However, the southwestern corner of the area received in excess of 150 percent of normal and parts of Maverick and Dimmit Counties had as much as four times normal. This rain allowed Kinney (now in extreme drought category, Stage D3), Dimmit (severe category, Stage D2), Maverick (D2), and Zavala (D2) Counties to improve their drought conditions. At the same time, the lack of rain led to drought conditions worsening to stage D3 in Bastrop and Lee Counties, and to stage D2 in Blanco, Burnet, Caldwell, Comal, Fayette, Gonzales, Guadalupe, Hays, Kendall, and Travis Counties. Val Verde (D4), Edwards (D3), Bandera (D2), De Witt (D2), Frio (D2), Gillespie (D2), Kerr (D2), Llano (D2), Medina (D2), Real (D2), Uvalde (D2), and Williamson (D2) Counties all remained unchanged from May. Fire danger at the end of the month was moderate. Of the counties in D2 or worse drought Caldwell, Dimmit, Edwards, Fayette, Frio, Kinney, Lee, Llano, Maverick, Medina, and Val Verde had outdoor burn bans in effect at the end of the month. The seven day stream flow averages were much below normal (less than 10 percent) across the Colorado River basin. The Upper and Middle Guadalupe, Nueces, Rio Grande, and Frio River basins were reporting below normal (10 to 24 percent) flow. Area lakes and reservoirs continued well below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was around 59 feet below normal. Lake Travis was 54 feet below normal and Medina Lake 83 feet below normal which left it at 5 percent of capacity. The Edwards Aquifer was nearly 17 feet below normal, and 3.2 feet below the level at the end of June 2012. Uvalde was in stage 5 water restrictions, Austin was in stage 2, and Kerrville, San Marcos, and Seguin were in stage 1. The Barton Springs Edwards Aquifer Conservation District was in stage 3 alarm drought status.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level low pressure center over northern Mexico combined with a very moist air mass over South Central Texas to cause showers and thunderstorms. Some of these storms produced very heavy rain that led to flash flooding in western parts of the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms produced heavy rain that caused flash flooding in Carrizo Springs. Several vehicles were stuck in high water at San Pedro Ave. and 3rd St.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Isolated weak showers developed during the afternoon and evening of June 7th over northeast Iowa along a nearly stationary trough of low pressure. Conditions were favorable for funnel clouds to develop despite the showers being very weak. No touchdowns were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A funnel cloud was spotted southeast of Waucoma.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A couple rounds of severe thunderstorms rolled across northeast Iowa during the afternoon and evening of June 12th. These storms developed ahead of an area of low pressure that was moving east across the Upper Midwest. The storms primarily produced high winds that blew down trees near Marquette (Clayton County) in the afternoon and around Nora Springs and Marble Rock (Floyd County) in the evening. Some quarter sized hail also fell in Oran (Fayette County).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down northwest of Marble Rock.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The residual cold airmass over the Oklahoma Panhandle from a cold frontal passage earlier in the week had begun to modify. This kept overnight low temperatures from cooling as quickly as previous nights. Freezing temperatures were not obtained until the early morning hours on the 4th. These subfreezing temperatures threatened sensitive vegetation during the start of the growing season. Overnight lows ranged from 26 degrees at Kenton (Cimarron County) to 32 degrees at Guymon (Texas County). Temperatures quickly warmed above freezing during the mid-morning of the 4th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An overnight low of 28 degrees was reported in Beaver.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong winds developed over portions of south central and eastern NM as a potent upper level trough slammed eastward across the region early on the 17th.  Widespread windy conditions were reported with areas across the south central high terrain experiencing wind gusts as high as 70mph. Some damage was also reported around the central and northeast highlands as the potent cold front pushed through the region.  Widespread blowing dust occurred with this event...where some locales reported visibilities below one half mile at times.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A vacant mobile home was overturned in Anton Chico as a dust storm descended on the area along a potent cold front.

The slow moving storms produced mainly wind damage with some hail as well as some flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Many trees were reported down across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Severe thunderstorms formed along an outflow boundary across the Mid South and moved into the Southern Appalachians during the afternoon and early evening. The result of the early Spring event was mostly wind damage along with some small hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported in Piney Flats.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed along various boundaries within a warm and moist air mass over the region. Storms first developed across the Finger Lakes midday along the Lake Ontario lake breeze and then in the mid afternoon along the Lake Erie lake breeze boundary as it pushed inland across the Southern Tier. The strongest storms produced one to two inch hailstones.  Specific hail reports were received from Stanley, Geneva, Newark, Walworth, Marion, and Brockport. In several of those locations, automobiles were damage by the hail stones.  Later in the afternoon thunderstorms rolled across the North Country with downed trees and power poles reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level low was across the eastern U.S. led to a prolonged fetch of warm moist air from the Atlantic.  A strong jet increased shear across the region and thunderstorms that developed were capable of wind damage and large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: There was water across the road and up the sidewalks.  Water is at least 12 to 18 inches deep on the side of the road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: May brought some much needed rain to South Central Texas. Much of the area received above normal rainfall and 14 counties moved to better than severe (Stage D2) drought. In addition, Bandera, Kerr, Medina, Real, Uvalde, and Williamson Counties improved a category to stage D2. All the other counties stayed the same with Kinney, Maverick, and Val Verde in exceptional (Stage D4) drought category, Dimmit, Edwards, and Zavala in extreme (Stage D3), and Bastrop, De Witt, Frio, Gillespie, Lee, and Llano in severe (Stage D2) category. Fire danger at the end of the month was low to moderate. Of the counties in D2 or worse drought seven had outdoor burn bans in effect at the end of the month. These were Dimmit, Edwards, Frio, Kinney, Maverick, Medina, and Val Verde. The seven day stream flow averages were much below normal (less than 10 percent) across the Colorado River basin. The Guadalupe, Nueces, Rio Grande, and Frio River basins were reporting below normal (10 to 24 percent) flow. Area lakes and reservoirs continued below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was around 61 feet below normal at 1056.3 feet which is a new record low for the lake. Lake Travis was 52 feet below normal and Medina Lake near 82 feet below normal which left it at 5.5 percent of capacity. The Edwards Aquifer saw some improvement from the rain in May, but was still 8 feet below normal, and 4.2 feet below the level at the end of May 2012. Uvalde was in stage 5 water restrictions and Kerrville was in stage 1.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: With a warm and moist airmass in place over the region, thunderstorms developed along lake breezes during the afternoon and evening.  The persistent storms were prolific hail producersnot only in size but quantity. At times it was reported the hail completely covered the ground. The largest stones approached two inches, however most of the hail exceeded one-inch in diameter.  Hail was reported near Lake Bluff, Port Bay, Red Creek, Victory, Martville, West Monroe and Hastings, to name a few. While most of the severe reports were of large hail, a few storms did produce damaging winds with trees and wires reported down near Ira, Victory, Phoenix, Wellsville, Adams Center and Batavia.

A warm and humid air mass was in place across the region on Sunday, June 2nd with temperatures well into the 80s.  A cold front and associated pre-frontal surface trough was moving towards the area during the afternoon hours.  With plenty of moisture and instability in place, showers and thunderstorms developed across the region.  These thunderstorms were aided by very strong winds aloft and a few storms became severe across northwestern Connecticut, producing large hail.  The thunderstorms weakened by evening as the cold front moved across the area, ending the threat for severe weather.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported during a thunderstorm in Barkhampsted Center.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very warm and humid air mass was located across northern New York and Vermont during the afternoon and evening hours of June 1st. A weak disturbance, well ahead of a cold front forecast to cross on June 2nd, triggered a few scattered thunderstorms in northern New York that produced damaging winds and weakened as it entered Vermont with only an isolated report of wind damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A large tree and several weaker trees downed by thunderstorm winds along Buck Hollow road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Individual severe thunderstorms that developed over South Central Wisconsin, producing hail up to 1 inch in diameter, merged into several squall lines that produced damaging wind gusts as they moved east through Southeast Wisconsin during the afternoon and evening hours of May 30th. Overall forcing for ascent over the region was provided by  differential vorticity advection ahead of a progressive 500 mb negatively-tilted trough, with the storms developing on the nose of a moderate to strong low-level jet ahead of the wave. Moderate instability, reflected in mixed-layer CAPE values of 1000 to 1200 J/kg, and favorable wind shear contributed to conditions that produced broken bands of thunderstorms with damaging wind gusts and downbursts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Law enforcement officials reported a few trees and power lines downed by thunderstorm wind gusts estimated at 65 mph (56 knots) in Newark.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong weather system moved through the region, triggering showers and thunderstorms.  There were numerous reports of large hail, as well as damaging winds and three tornadoes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A line of severe thunderstorms moved through the Union area.  Several large trees were blown down as well as numerous tree limbs.  A business on the north side of town had minor roof damage. A microburst occurred on the south side of town at the First Baptist Church.  The attached brick building had the majority of its metal roof peeled off with insulation thrown downwind toward the intersection of East Main Street and Highway 47.  Other small trees were observed to be snapped off in this area in addition to minor shingle damage to the roof of the church itself.  The estimated wind speed in this location was 70 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving cold front and associated pre frontal trough approached upstate New York during the afternoon hours on June 17th, 2013.  With temperatures into the 80s and high levels of moisture in place, there was plenty of instability available for thunderstorms to develop.  A line of thunderstorms developed across the Capital Region and strong winds aloft aided in allowing these storms to become severe with damaging winds and large hail.  By later in the afternoon, the thunderstorms tracked east and away from the region, ending the threat for severe weather.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were reported down on Route 4 in Fort Edward due to thunderstorm winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: May brought some much needed rain to South Central Texas. Much of the area received above normal rainfall and 14 counties moved to better than severe (Stage D2) drought. In addition, Bandera, Kerr, Medina, Real, Uvalde, and Williamson Counties improved a category to stage D2. All the other counties stayed the same with Kinney, Maverick, and Val Verde in exceptional (Stage D4) drought category, Dimmit, Edwards, and Zavala in extreme (Stage D3), and Bastrop, De Witt, Frio, Gillespie, Lee, and Llano in severe (Stage D2) category. Fire danger at the end of the month was low to moderate. Of the counties in D2 or worse drought seven had outdoor burn bans in effect at the end of the month. These were Dimmit, Edwards, Frio, Kinney, Maverick, Medina, and Val Verde. The seven day stream flow averages were much below normal (less than 10 percent) across the Colorado River basin. The Guadalupe, Nueces, Rio Grande, and Frio River basins were reporting below normal (10 to 24 percent) flow. Area lakes and reservoirs continued below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was around 61 feet below normal at 1056.3 feet which is a new record low for the lake. Lake Travis was 52 feet below normal and Medina Lake near 82 feet below normal which left it at 5.5 percent of capacity. The Edwards Aquifer saw some improvement from the rain in May, but was still 8 feet below normal, and 4.2 feet below the level at the end of May 2012. Uvalde was in stage 5 water restrictions and Kerrville was in stage 1.

All the other counties stayed the same with Kinney, Maverick, and Val Verde in exceptional (Stage D4) drought category, Dimmit, Edwards, and Zavala in extreme (Stage D3), and Bastrop, De Witt, Frio, Gillespie, Lee, and Llano in severe (Stage D2) category. Fire danger at the end of the month was low to moderate. Of the counties in D2 or worse drought seven had outdoor burn bans in effect at the end of the month. These were Dimmit, Edwards, Frio, Kinney, Maverick, Medina, and Val Verde. The seven day stream flow averages were much below normal (less than 10 percent) across the Colorado River basin. The Guadalupe, Nueces, Rio Grande, and Frio River basins were reporting below normal (10 to 24 percent) flow. Area lakes and reservoirs continued below normal pool elevations. Lake Amistad was around 61 feet below normal at 1056.3 feet which is a new record low for the lake. Lake Travis was 52 feet below normal and Medina Lake near 82 feet below normal which left it at 5.5 percent of capacity. The Edwards Aquifer saw some improvement from the rain in May, but was still 8 feet below normal, and 4.2 feet below the level at the end of May 2012. Uvalde was in stage 5 water restrictions and Kerrville was in stage 1.

A weak upper level wave helped to spark a line of thunderstorms along a surface trough across the eastern New Mexico Plains and into the Central Plains during the evening hours of the 16th.  A few isolated storms developed across the southern Texas Panhandle ahead of the main line of storms and moved to the southeast. These discrete thunderstorms brought primarily severe hail to the Texas Panhandle. The thunderstorms that developed along the surface trough formed into a broken linear structure due to areas of higher instability and stronger deep layer shear. The linear structure made the primary hazard for these storms damaging winds. A line of thunderstorms which moved through the southern Texas Panhandle during the overnight hours of the 16th and into the early morning hours of the 17th took on a classic bow echo signature. As a result, severe wind damage was noted in southern Randall County where the bow echo signature first developed. Thunderstorms moved to the southeast across the Panhandles before entering northwest Texas by 2 AM CST.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Discrete thunderstorms developed over the southern Texas Panhandle during the evening hours of the 16th. One of these thunderstorms developed over northern Carson County and moved to the south-southeast across the county. A trained storm spotter 2 miles east of Conway (Carson County) reported ping pong size hail (1.50 inches) as the thunderstorm moved overhead. The thunderstorm continued to move to the south-southeast across the county after producing this hail.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A disturbance moved across the Billings Forecast Area during the late morning hours on the 13th that resulted in severe thunderstorms that lasted into the early morning hours of the 14th. Strong daytime heating along with 40-50 knots of southwesterly mid-level flow resulted in a very unstable atmosphere that was conducive for supercell thunderstorms.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Public reported penny-sized hail and very gusty winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorm complex that developed in conjunction with a strengthening surface low over northern Indiana propagated westward towards the region late on the 12th. Out ahead of this system, strong speed shear and instability contributed to supercellular development along a warm frontal boundary that bisected the region. Several reports of large hail and damaging winds were reported before the bow echo reached eastern Ohio very early on the 13th. This bow echo, with a history of widespread wind damage, then crossed through the forecast area through 6am, causing several reports of downed trees and wires through much of eastern Ohio, northern West Virginia, and southwestern Pennsylvania.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Local law enforcement reported a tree down blocking Gilkeson Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An outflow boundary situated over interstate 80 became the focus for thunderstorm development as several upper level disturbances rounded a flattening ridge over the plains. These storms eventually congealed into several lines, one near the western Pennsylvania/Ohio border and another further back into Ohio southern lower Michigan, that moved southeastward through the evening of the 25th and early on the 26th. In addition to widespread reports of wind damage and hail, training thunderstorms dumped two to four inches of rain and caused areas of flooding across east central Ohio and adjacent areas in western Pennsylvania.
